@node "Save and Save As"

                             SAVE AND SAVE AS.

QUESTION:-

        I am very new to the Amiga and although using a number of word
processors am confused between the SAVE and SAVE AS options. When I save
files they go on the program disk which is quickly filled up because there

isn't much space spare. When I try to save to a blank disk my program tent
to ask for the program's own disk to inserted.


ANSWER:-
        As a general rule you shouldn't save your data files to the disk
the programs are on. It's bad practice for two reasons: firstly, some
programs have copy protection schemes that can actually cause a program on
a disk to stop working if the disk's file contents are changed, Secondly,
because saving files on a program disk means that you have to keep that
disk 'writeable' it also means that the disk could become infected with a
virus. You really ought to write protect your program disks by sliding the
write protect notch over to the side where you can see through the hole
(although you will find the odd game program etc., that requires the
program disk to be kept as writeable)! With that lecture over, your SAVE
and SAVE AS problems are easy to explain. The first time you save a file
you should use SAVE AS because this allows you to give the file a name
chosen by you. Even if your word-processor programs bring up a system
requester asking for the program disk to be inserted initially you can
usually either just cancel the requester or, once the real file requester
appears and the drive light goes out, just swap to your blank disk and
click on df0: (or whatever drive you have you blank disk in) to 'log in'
(ie. read the root directory of) that new disk. At this point the file
requester will show you the drive and directory that your file will
currently be stored in but you can change these items using the file
requester gadgets at any point up to where you click on the file
requester's OK (or similar) box. You normally only use SAVE to update an
existing file that you have re-opened for further editing!



